<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1068" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1068">Distribution</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1068">
Holarctic, known from arctic Russia (Kanin Peninsula, as 
<taxonomicName genus="Brachycampta" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Brachycampta arctica" pageId="0" pageNumber="1068" rank="species" species="arctica">Brachycampta arctica</taxonomicName>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Lundstroem, C." journalOrPublisher="Acta Societatis pro Fauna et Flora Fennica" pageId="0" pageNumber="1068" pagination="1 - 20" title="Beitrag zur Kenntnis der Dipterenfauna des Noerdl. Europaeischen Russland" volume="37" year="1913">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Lundström">Lundstroem</normalizedToken>
and Frey 1913
</bibRefCitation>
), Russian Karelia and Murmansk region (
<bibRefCitation author="Polevoi, A. V." journalOrPublisher="Karelian Research Centre, Russian Academy of Sciences, Petrozavodsk" pageId="0" pageNumber="1068" title="Fungus gnats (Diptera: Bolitophilidae, Ditomyiidae, Keroplatidae, Diadocidiidae, Mycetophilidae) in Karelia." year="2000">Polevoi 2000</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Polevoi, A. V." journalOrPublisher="Trudy Karel'skogo NC RAN. Seriya biogeografiya" pageId="0" pageNumber="1068" pagination="95 - 104" title="Fungus gnats (Diptera: Bolitophilidae, Keroplatidae, Mycetophilidae) of Pasvik strict nature reserve" volume="10" year="2010">Polevoi 2010</bibRefCitation>
), Ireland (
<bibRefCitation author="Chandler, P." journalOrPublisher="Proceedings and transactions of the British Entomological and Natural History Society" pageId="0" pageNumber="1068" pagination="71 - 85" title="Some fungus gnats of the tribe Exechiini (Dipt., Mycetophilidae) new to the British Isles" volume="10" year="1977">Chandler 1977</bibRefCitation>
), Central Europe (
<bibRefCitation pageId="0" pageNumber="1068">Chandler 2004</bibRefCitation>
) and USA (
<bibRefCitation author="Zaitzev, A. I." journalOrPublisher="Entomologichekoe obozrenie" pageId="0" pageNumber="1068" pagination="391 - 404" title="Fungus gnats of the sericoma, griseicolle and ruficorne species groups of the genus Brevicornu Marshall (Diptera, Mycetophilidae) of Holarctic fauna" volume="67" year="1988">Zaitzev 1988</bibRefCitation>
). In the Nordic countries recorded from Sweden and Norway (
<bibRefCitation pageId="0" pageNumber="1068">Kjaerandsen 2012</bibRefCitation>
). Perhaps a boreo-montane species (
<bibRefCitation author="Kjaerandsen, J." journalOrPublisher="Insect Systematics &amp; Evolution, Supplement" pageId="0" pageNumber="1068" pagination="1 - 165" title="Annotated checklist of fungus gnats from Sweden (Diptera: Bolitophilidae, Diadocidiidae, Ditomyiidae, Keroplatidae and Mycetophilidae)" volume="65" year="2007">Kjaerandsen et al. 2007</bibRefCitation>
). New for Finland.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1068" type="ecology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1068">Ecology</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1068">
Finnish sampling localities are headwater streams surrounded by pristine or seminatural boreal forests. Immature stages are unknown. In their larval habitats, 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Mycetophilidae" genus="Brevicornu" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Brevicornu" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1068" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Brevicornu</taxonomicName>
do not resemble closely related species of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Mycetophilidae" genus="Allodia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Allodia" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1068" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Allodia</taxonomicName>
. At least some 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Mycetophilidae" genus="Brevicornu" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Brevicornu" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1068" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Brevicornu</taxonomicName>
species develop in dead wood and in soil litter, feeding probably on microfungi (
<bibRefCitation author="Jakovlev, J." journalOrPublisher="Entomologica Fennica" pageId="0" pageNumber="1068" pagination="157 - 189" title="Fungus gnats (Diptera: Sciaroidea) associated with dead wood and wood growing fungi: new rearing data from Finland and Russian Karelia and general analysis of known larval microhabitats in Europe" volume="22" year="2011">Jakovlev 2011a</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
